  "prompt": "What is the square root of 40 in radical form?",
  "response": "The square root of 40 can be simplified in radical form. \n\nFirst, we can factor 40 into its prime factors:\n\n\\[\n40 = 4 \\times 10 = 4 \\times 2 \\times 5\n\\]\n\nSince 4 is a perfect square, we can take the square root of 4 out of the radical:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{40} = \\sqrt{4 \\times 10} = \\sqrt{4} \\times \\sqrt{10} = 2\\sqrt{10}\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the square root of 40 in radical form is:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{40} = 2\\sqrt{10}\n\\]",
